[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **The unauthenticated-public-website-channel is the recipe-distinct dimension.** The recipe lists web chat widget, in-app chat, SMS, secure-messaging gateway, and third-party messenger as channels (correctly), and correctly elevates that the FAQ bot can serve unauthenticated users (correctly, as a privacy-by-design choice). Despite this, the architecture does not specify the per-channel session-token discipline, the per-channel session-timeout-and-isolation policy, or the cross-channel session-bridging discipline. A web-chat session that began at 8 PM Tuesday and continued at 9 PM Tuesday under the same browser session is the same conversation; a new session at 9 PM Wednesday is a different conversation. The architecture should specify the session-boundary policy, the session-token TTL, and the per-channel session-isolation primitives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **The shared-device problem is recipe-distinct.** The recipe correctly notes in Where-it-Struggles that "A family member uses the same browser session as the patient. The bot's conversation history may persist and surface in the next session" with the mitigation "Short session timeouts for unauthenticated chat sessions, no sensitive content (the FAQ bot does not handle sensitive content by design) so the worst case is an awkward but not harmful surface." The architecture should specify the session-timeout values per channel, the session-clear-on-channel-close discipline, the no-cross-session-history-leak invariant, and the optional explicit-clear-conversation patient affordance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **The inadvertent-PHI-volunteered-by-user redaction discipline is named but not specified.** The Step 2C `phi_detector.evaluate(text: user_message)` call returns a generic phi_signal with categories; the architecture does not specify the redaction taxonomy (medical-condition-mention, medication-mention, account-number-mention, family-member-name-mention, date-of-birth-mention, address-mention, employer-name-mention, etc.), the per-language detection discipline (a Spanish-language patient mentioning "diabetes" or "lupus" should redact the same as the English equivalent), the per-category redaction-or-redirect policy (some categories warrant redaction-and-continue; some warrant redirect-and-handoff), the redaction-confidence-and-review workflow (false-negative cases where the detector missed PHI become a quality concern), and the redaction-versus-PHI-archive discipline (where does the original utterance live; how long does the unredacted version persist; who has access).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **The patient-rights-request workflow is correctly elevated in production-gaps but not architecturally specified.** A patient who asks "what conversations have I had with the chatbot, and can I delete them" is asking a question the architecture should answer: how the patient submits the request (via the institutional patient-rights surface; via the chat widget itself), how the institution authenticates the request (since the FAQ bot is mostly unauthenticated, the authentication happens through the patient's existing institutional identity flow), how the conversation history is produced (correlation key from authenticated patient identity to the unauthenticated session-tokens that may have been used; the institution may not have this correlation), how patients can request deletion (subject to legal-hold and Object-Lock-in-compliance-mode retention requirements; the deletion is replaced with a deletion-marker for the regulatory-retention period), and how the workflow integrates with the institution's existing patient-rights handling.
